Absolutely mind boggling that @Strategy is still levering up. They're selling $MSTR shares that are worth 80 cents on the dollar to buy $1 dollar bills. Relative to its BTC holdings after accounting for debt and preferred equity liabilities, MSTR common trades at ~0.8x NAV. This behaviors tells me the market's message needs to get louder for it to be understood.

@twitconomics @Strategy We are

@DylanLeClair @Strategy Thanks! I mostly disagree with his use of proceeds. Agree $MSTR is the release valve that gets hit and will continue to, but think he should be fortifying balance sheet instead of continuing to buy BTC. $MSTR holders will throw the towel in more definitively eventually.

MSTR from an investor's perspective is extremely risky as a result of the senior claims and its large premium to liquidation value.

Common equity issuance at any price is always credit positive to the capital structure, which benefits credit and senior equity holders at the expense of common equity holders.

The purchase of BTC with its cash reserves, by a company that generates severely negative cash flow equal to a ~4%+ annual common equity dilution rate and is solely reliant on capital markets financing to support its debt service and preferred equity obligations, is not credit positive.

